<dl id="un2039a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2039">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un2all.htm#un2039a"> (VI.D.7) 39(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Troy fair &mdash; July &mdash; Castle lord</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">One can reconstruct the scene. It begins in July, when the Paphlagonians have had two good months for their long coasting voyage. The actual <mark>fair</mark> takes place on the low, nearly level ridge at the end of which stands the castle of <mark>Troy</mark>. The <mark>lord of the castle</mark> is the presiding genius of the scene &hellip; <small> Walter Leaf, <a name="WLAS" href="/udra/udex.htm#wlas"><cite title="source">Troy: A Study in Homeric Geography</cite></a> (1912), 314</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c16265d" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16265d">VI.C.16:265(d)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
